I loved this nozzle cooler for my powerspec 3d pro. However with my aluminum carriages, the duct would hang lower than my nozzle.

To correct this I made the duct part thinner. In doing so I reduced air flow. To fix this i moved the fan back a little and tilted it.

This should be compatible with any replicator 2x clone; ctc, powerspec, flashforge ...etc

REV_1.0:
Change: Duct thinned, fan moved back;
Result: Airflow not as good as original, but not as thick as REV_2.0
REV_1.5:
Change: Duct thinned, fan moved back, fan tilted 70 degrees;
Result: Airflow improved from original
REV_2.0:
Change: Duct thinned, fan moved back further than REV_1.0;
Result: Airflow as good as the original.

description.text:
!!!FINAL DESIGN !!!

This is a simple 8 inch shelf bracket that i designed for a 10-12 inch shelf. This shelf bracket is crazy strong I'm even surprised at how strong this is myself. It's even able to hold about 70 lbs by itself and 40 lbs at the very tip of the shelf bracket itself!!! And yes it's holding 2 cinder blocks and 2 fire bricks and it still could handle more!

After a stress weight test, I've found out that the current design can hold over 120-130+ lbs, The brackets failed at 170+ lbs.

Changes:
Moved the screw holds to allow for stronger hold to the wall and shelf.

Complete redesign of the structural supports and no holes going through any structure.

Supports are thinner than the rest of the bracket allowing for a screwdriver/drill to pass by while installing bracket.

Lowered one of the wall mounting screw holes to allow for easier install and to keep screws from potentially colliding.

removed a top shelf holddown screw hole for added strength

**removed a wall mount screw for added strength

** added a small taper at the top corner for added strength

Please leave any feedback you might have as I appreciate any suggestions for future designs.

description.text:
Take on the role of an antiques appraiser and research this artifact. Which president is associated with this artifact and what presidential power does it represent? The more information you provide, the more valuable the artifact.

This 3D printable model was created by a student in Ms. Relator's US Government class at Dominion HS in Virginia. Find out more about the Mystery Artifact lesson at https://www.lcps.org/Page/186358

Mystery artifact created by,

Emma Karren

-He became the only ex-President to serve in the U.S. House of Representatives in 1830
-He has the same first and last name as his father (who served as the 2nd president of the U.S.)
-The ivory cane is made by Julius Pratt & Company of Meriden, Connecticut.
-It was given to this President for his efforts to end the gag rule, which prevented discussions in the House of Representatives about the abolition of slavery.

The Object:
A Cane

Details about the Object:
This president noted in his diary: “There is in the top of the cane a golden eagle inlaid, bearing a scroll, with the motto ‘Right of Petition Triumphant’ engraved upon it. The donors requested of me that when the gag-rule should be rescinded I would cause the date to be added to the motto.” (Smithsonian Institution)

President:
John Quincy Adams served from 1825 to 1829. Adams was the last Democratic-Republican to be elected President.

Presidential Role:
This illustrates the ‘Chief Legislature’ power of the president.

Presidential Action:
Adams argued that slavery contradicted the principals of Republicanism. Adams expressed his disapproval of slavery by writing letters about the dangers posed by abolitionists groups who promoted slavery.

"Adams opposed the institution of slavery on moral principle—as a violation of human beings’ inalienable right to liberty, and as incitement to a spirit of mastery dangerous to republican politics in America Adams’ public arguments allowed him to make clear his respect for traditional political limits on how the national government might address slavery in America." (Intercollegiate Studies Institute)

Impact on America:
I chose this President and artifact because this ivory cane was given to John Quincy Adams by Julius Pratt & Company of Meriden, Connecticut for his efforts to end the gag rule, which prevented discussions in the House of Representatives about the abolition of slavery. Adams argued that the gag-rule violated the constitutional right to petition- a right that extended even to slaves. Adams fought to restore fundamental and constitutional freedom until the slavery gag-rule was suspended. This marked a major turning point in the fight to end slavery.

description.text:
Hi, This is a variation on a Tape Measure Car racer I saw on Youtube and made to give students doing a BTEC Project unit some ideas on how they could design a similar car.
The initial vehicle seen used CD's or DVD's as wheels, my original design had only 3 wheels as I wanted to show progression and design development through modifications.

The first modification I made was to design new wheels for the rear which I printed and then fitted them with a printed tyre from Ninjaflex. When we again tried to run the vehicle it did provide better traction but we had problems with the steering, the vehicle tended to steer to one side and then tip over, although it did travel faster than with the final design.

The second modification was to change the front wheel, the same feature was used to hold the steering wheel but modified to hold 2 wheels, this gave a lot better stability and steering control which also resulted in less crashes.

Parts Printer using a Makerbot Replicator 2X at Bradford College - UK and the front wheels made from Aluminium or could be printed from the students own design. The rear Axle was turned from Nylon and we stepped this so that it increased the speed as the racer ran the tape out. The rear axle ran in 2 needle bearings approx. 7/16" (12mm) OD and 1/4" (6mm) ID these can be glued to the body when the rear axle is completed.

TheTape measure length needs to be agreed by students if you are to race these so that no unfair advantage is gained from using different tapes i.e 5Metre, 7.5M or 10M lengths.

Pull out the tape coil and clamp it so that the coil does not rewind, then cut the coil as required, drill a small hole in the tape and attach your string, line, wire as you see fit. Slowly allow the tape measure to pull in the string, once fully re-wound attach the string to the rear axle.
**** Note - if you tie a solid knot to the rear axle the racer will stop suddenly and then reverse as the string is wound back into the tape. (do you tell student this or let them find out themselves). Look on the photo's for hints to stop this.

Once completed you can race these, challenge students - to make the fastest, the longest travel, lightest, etc.

The Bradford College racer managed nearly 7MPH which we video'd and then used software to calculate the speed over a 3 Meter distance, use 2 video camera's synchronised (started) at the same time so frame rates are constant. Have 1st camera aimed at the start tape and the 2nd camera aimed at the second tape 3 metres away.

We also managed a distance of the full length of the workshop Atrium at college, how far will yours go ?.

See the attached photo's of the race and calculations.

Additional activities then include speed calculations, conversion of speed in metres to MPH. Measuring distance travelled or weight of items.

description.text:
Note:
V1 for this was here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2099034
It broke after a few weeks of use (https://goo.gl/photos/5fpRg7m1fgBkHXUp9)
So I designed a much more rigid part that will probably last much longer.

This is part of a project in which I converted my longboard into an electric longboard for my kid. I mount 4S 5200mAh lipo on it for the kid, but it can hold 2 or even 3 packs stacked if you don't mind the hight. There is room for velcro straps on the sides, but those are not needed when mounting a single pack.

There are pros and cons for using LIPO over lithium-ion cells which are more often used, and there are pros and cons for mounting it on top of the board (instead of beneath it) . Keep those in mind when making a decision.

Pros:

  • Lipos are easier to source (when counting the spot-welding involved in li-ions, at least where I live), there are some bargains in stores like Hobbyking.
  • For those with RC background, charging, balancing and monitoring lipos is easy.
  • Since you can carry spares in your backpack, it is easy to create a lite and adaptive setup (both for different range and for different speeds)
  • Mounting on top means that you see the battery (if something happens to it).
  • Mounting on top makes cheap and simple monitoring easier (just hook a battery monitor).

Cons:

  • Lipos are much less safe than li-ion. (please understand this risk)
  • Lipos wear out much quicker
  • Mounting on top means you can trip on the battery
  • Mounting on top means you can step on the battery (You can design a top cover to avoid it)

description.text:
I wanted to experiment with simple low-cost DC motors and see how easy it would be to make my own 3D designs to convert their high speed, low torque attributes into something more usable. So I designed this gear experiment set that lets you position and fix various gear sizes onto a matrix board. You can then drive the input with a commonly available DC motor or a crank handle option. I added a linear piston as an output device and also a spinning thing, but this is just a bit of a novelty.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2tM8FO0YgnI

The gears have various diameters; 50, 45, 40, 35, 30, 25, 20 and 15 mm
All of them have a 10mm inner spindle gear.

The 8 x 8 cm matrix boards have M3 holes space at 5mm.

Use M3 x 20mm screws to hold the gears in place. I did try printing some 3mm pins for this but they are not so easy to print and were too weak. You can also print the stand-off feet the raise up the matrix boards to give space underneath for any excess screw length or if you want to secure them with a 3mm nut.

The motor is commonly available in eBay of from Chinese internal sites like Banggood. It is 20mm wide x 15mm in height and is 38mm in length measure from the spindle ends. The spindle is 2mm. Just search 3v DC motor and choose the flat more elliptical shaped ones, not the round ones

The DC motor controller and battery holder are also easily obtained from eBay sellers or banggood.com
Search:
Low Voltage DC 1.8V 3V 5V 6V 12V 2A Motor Speed Controller PWM

There is an option to fix the motor both horizontally with a bevel gears or vertically.

In use, it can be a bit temperamental and may jam up sometimes, but that’s part of the fun in getting it going. The m3 screws can sometime tighten themselves if it’s running fast gear can pop off so there could be secured with double M3 nuts. I’ve created recesses in the latest gear design to accommodate the screw heads. Screws of 25mm or longer may be used it necessary.

Tip: Only drive the out rings from other outer rings or the 10mm inner rings. It needs too much torque if you try to drive the 10mm inner ring from a larger outer ring.

The matrix boards seem to take forever to slice. I use Slic3r and it has to be left for hours!

List of STLs

GearBase80mm.stl - 8 x 8 cm matrix baseboard
BevelGear.stl - 30cm Bevel gear & drive pinion for motor
MotorHousing.stl - Holds the motor on the matrix board horizontally (use with bevel gear)
Motor90Bracket.stl - Allows the motor to mounted at 90° and used with a regular 10mm gear
PowerBox.stl - Holds the batteries and DC motor controller.
Handle.stl - All parts to make the hand crank
LinearPiston.stl - The long shaft, conrod, end cap and holder for the piston
LinearPistonPins.stl - Pins to connect the conrod and piston together.
Spinner.stl - three parts to make the spinny thing
StandOff.stl - the feet for the matrix boards

15mmGear.stl, 20mmGear.stl, 25mmGear.stl, 30mmGear.stl, 35mmGear.stl, 40mmGear.stl, 45mmGear.stl, 50mmGear.stl
The gears. Print as needed. the medium to large sizes are more useful. These are a later design. the images show some plain green gears but I updated them to look more interesting.

Everything is designed to print without supports. Standard infill of around 20% is normally fine, but you can increase if necessary.

This is a vibration isolator for Trinus 3D printer. Using the magic of magnetic repulsion the top half will levitate to prevent vibration towards the table and floor. I also noticed a reduction on harmonic vibration in the room. While the printer still makes noise, the amplification is minimized.

Note:
Due to the weight of the Trinus printer, you will need to order strong rare earth magnets.

Finally, since the printer is heavier in the back end this will cause a slight lean back due to the weight. Don't worry the print will still be leveled since the extruder and printer bed are on the same axis. (you can level this out by reducing the magnetic power of the front magnets, get smaller ones)

title: Pointy lamp shade
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
The Philips Hue lamps are so awesome, it would be a shame not to make my own lamp shades with it. I needed to buy fittings anyway.
This model is the first of three. I thought it would be nice to generate this lamp shade given some geometric shapes. I designed it as a tabletop model. Both parts can be printed in a single go without support. Make sure your fitting has 2 screws on the outside, so you can clamp the parts in between. Accidently, it also quite looks nice with just the top part.
The hole is 42mm diameter to fit my E27 fittings. Source code is included, so you can adjust as needed.

Materials and methods

I used transparent PLA, which perfectly fits the need. The build plate must be at least something like 210x210x152mm.

My son LOVES the Replicator, and has trouble concentrating on math, so I generated a set of math flash cards using the Replicator.
The problem is on one side, and the answer is on the other. The cards contain every combination of 1+1, 1+2, ... through 9+9.

If you have a Replicator dualstruder, you can put the attached s3g file on an SD card and print it. Give them to your kid(s) so that they can practice addition. Otherwise, you can:
  • Merge the two STL files, using your preferred skein forge settings. The geometry is rendered properly located and centered to print on the Replicator, so don't do any manipulation in ReplicatorG (which could cause the geometry not to align). You don't need a raft. "Black" is the text, and "White" is the cards. Of course, you can use whatever colors you like. I'm leaning towards "glow in the dark" and "white",
  • Edit the STL to change the problems, etc. You will need write.scad (elsewhere on thingiverse) to render the text. For example, you can generate multiplication problems instead of addition problems.
    • Disclaimer: there are tons of tiny cards, and (at least for me) not all of them stick, so you will want to watch the print and pull off any cards that come loose so that the remaining cards print cleanly. There are 81 cards, and I lost perhaps ten in printing. That's plenty to keep my son busy!

Couldn't get the SSBT to remain parallel to each other, which resulted in the part rubbing on my belts.

I liked nonlinear's idea of flipping the tail and turning it into a dove tail joint, but the belt tension kept cracking his GT2 tensioners, so I designed this remix.

BOM:
1 m3x25mm Screw
1m3 nyloc nut

Once both parts are printed, slide the m3 nut into the rectangular cavity. The screw goes through the end with the dovetail.

Bolt "Tensioner 2" to the mounting holes of the belt screw, and loop your belt through the loop in Tensioner 1. Then run the screw from "Tensioner 1" through "Tensioner 2" insuring that the dovetail is securely mated. Then simply screw until proper belt tension is achieved.

Works for both X and Y axis belts.

Notes:

The following is needed to create one set of the puzzle:

  • 1 × A.stl
  • 1 × B.stl
  • 1 × C.stl
  • 1 × D.stl
  • 1 × E1.stl
  • 1 × E2.stl
  • 1 × F1.stl
  • 1 × F2.stl
  • 1 × G1.stl
  • 1 × G2.stl
  • 1 × H.stl
  • 1 × I.stl
  • 3 × Connector.stl

Note: E2.stl, F2.stl, and G2.stl are identical.

I used a no-name brand wood filament to print these.

Glue

I used CA glue to connect the separated cubes to the other main pieces using the connectors. Be careful not to get any glue on the outside surfaces!

Sand

Sand all the flat areas of the pieces with 180 grit sand paper. No need to sand all the chamfered areas.

Stain

For my project, I used a DIY coffee stain I found from here. Not only is it super cheap, it also smells wonderful!

Finish

I used a cheap clear spray lacquer to coat all the pieces. It should prevent the stain from rubbing off on other surfaces.

title: Beefy arms for Balboa balancing robot

description.text:
Is your Pololu Balboa 32U4 balancing robot falling over and hurting itself? Buff it up with a set of beefy arms! These adjustable support arms mount to the side of the Balboa chassis and help protect its electronics from hitting things if the robot loses its balance or runs into an obstacle.

Note that adding these arms will significantly change your Balboa's weight and center of mass; you'll probably have to tune your balancing code to work with them!
Print two pairs of arms with support. Attach them to the side rails on the Balboa chassis with four 25 mm M3 screws and nuts.
